]\n| author = Jay Sharbutt\n| date = 1990-12-11\n}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{IMDb title|0099276|Clarence}}\n</ref>\nIt is a sequel to the 1946 film ''[[It's a Wonderful Life]]'' following the character of [[Clarence Odbody]] from that film.\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is set in December 1989. The only continuing character from the original film is the [[guardian angel]], [[Clarence Odbody|Clarence]], played here by [[Robert Carradine]]. The plot is very similar to the 1946 film, with [[Kate Trotter]] playing  Rachel Logan, the human who needs Clarence's assistance.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Cast listing|\n* [[Robert Carradine]] as [[Clarence Odbody]]\n* [[Kate Trotter]] as Rachel Logan\n* [[Louis Del Grande]] as Brimmer\n* Richard Fitzpatrick as Jeremy\n* [[Barbara Hamilton (actor)|Barbara Hamilton]] as Mrs. Duckworth\n* [[Jamie Rainey]] as Casey\n* [[Nicolas Van Burek]] as Brent\n* [[Jason McSkimming]] as Joseph\n* [[Larry Aubrey]] as Bert\n* [[Rachel Blanchard]] as Jill\n}}\n\n==Release==\nThe film was made for TV and did not have a theatrical release. It was first broadcast on [[The Family Channel (United States)|The Family Channel]] on November 24, 1990.\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|0099276|Clarence}}\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{Eric Till}}\n{{It's a Wonderful Life}}\n\n[[Category:1990 television films]]\n[[Category:Canadian comedy films]]\n[[Category:Canadian films]]\n[[Category:Canadian Christmas films]]\n[[Category:Canadian sequel films]]\n[[Category:Canadian television films]]\n[[Category:Christmas television films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Eric Till]]\n[[Category:Television sequel films]]\n[[Category:Films about angels]]\n\n\n{{1990s-Canada-film-stub}}\n{{Christmas-tv-film-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Gonnym", "label": "safe", "comment": "update links after RM", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Clarence_(1990_film)"}
{"title_page": "Declan McKenna", "text_new": "{{short description|English singer-songwriter and musician (born 1998)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- Individual -->\n| name             = Declan McKenna\n| image            = Declan McKenna, Patterns, Brighton (Great Escape 2018) (40780741260) (cropped).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McKenna at [[The Great Escape Festival]] 2018\n| landscape        = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Declan Benedict McKenna\n| birth_place      = [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[Greater London]], England\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1998|12|24|df=y}}\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|mandolin}}\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|musician}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|High Quality Popular Music}}\n| associated_acts  = Superfood, Feet, Etchells, Zimmo, Scors, [[Osquello]], [[Clairo]] \n| website          = {{URL|www.declanmckenna.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Declan Benedict McKenna'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/writer/808716719/MCKENNA%20DECLAN%20BENEDICT|title=ASCAP Ace Search|last=McKenna|first=Declan Benedict|publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP)|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> (born 24 December 1998) is an English singer, songwriter, and musician. He initially gained recognition for winning the [[Glastonbury Festival]]'s Emerging Talent Competition in 2015. McKenna self-released the song \"Brazil\", a protest song criticising [[FIFA]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] held in Brazil, as his debut single in December 2014. It gained recognition after its re-release in August 2015. It reached number one on [[Sirius XM Radio]]'s [[Alt Nation]] Alt 18 Countdown for 23 January 2016 and held that spot for three weeks. The song also reached number 16 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart, number 45 in Japan and number 135 in France. His popularity attracted the attention of many major music labels; he eventually signed to [[Columbia Records]] in 2016.\n\nMcKenna continued to write and record music for his debut studio album during 2016. During this time, he also performed concerts and appeared at festivals. He released ''[[What Do You Think About the Car?]]'' through Columbia on 21 July 2017. Songs that appear on the album that were released as singles prior to the album\u2019s release include \"Paracetamol\", \"Isombard\" and \"The Kids Don't Wanna Come Home\", which peaked at number 84 on Belgium's [[Ultratop|Ultratop Flanders]] chart. Also during 2017, he made appearances at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] and [[Lollapalooza]] festivals.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life and breakout with \"Brazil\" (1998\u20132015)===\nDeclan McKenna was born in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[Greater London]],<ref>https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=declan%20&lastname=mckenna&eventyear=1998&eventyear_offset=1</ref> on 24 December 1998<ref name=\"welch\" /><ref name=smythz>{{cite news|last=Smyth|first=David|title=Declan McKenna, interview: The voice of Generation Z|work=The Evening Standard|date=6 January 2017|accessdate=6 January 2017|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/declan-mckenna-interview-the-voice-of-generation-z-a3434331.html}}</ref> and grew up in [[Cheshunt]], [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=\"wilkinson\">{{cite news|title=New Music of the Day: Declan McKenna \u2013 Paracetamol|last=Wilkinson|first=Matt|date=22 November 2015|work=[[NME]]}}</ref> where he attended [[St Mary's Church of England High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Waltham-Cross-summer-fair-provides-eclectic-entertainment-SLIDESHOW/story-21986168-detail/story.html#8|title=Waltham Cross summer fair provides eclectic entertainment: Slideshow|work=Hertfordshire Mercury|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=8 January 2016}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He began taking his [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] exams in the summer of 2015.<ref name=\"welch\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Glastonbury-Festival-competition-winner-Declan/story-28341626-detail/story.html |title=Glastonbury Festival competition winner Declan McKenna is one to watch |last=Welch |first=Andy |date=12 December 2015 |work=Bristol Post |access-date=8 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220113233/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Glastonbury-Festival-competition-winner-Declan/story-28341626-detail/story.html |archive-date=20 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=bbc /> He later studied for his [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A-levels]] in English literature, Philosophy and Ethics, and Sociology, but stopped after a few months after his music career began to consume too much of his time.<ref name=smythz />\n\nIn 2015, McKenna entered the Glastonbury Festival's Emerging Talent Competition. The festival named him the winner of the contest in April 2015,<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02v4y9m|title=New Talent at Glastonbury|work=BBC News|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=brinsford>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/james-brinsford/why-glastonbury-2015-will_b_7065156.html|last=Brinsford|first=Brinsford|title=10 Reasons Why Glastonbury 2015 May Be the Greatest Show on Earth|work=Huffington Post|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> for which he was awarded a \u00a35,000 prize and a slot on the festival's William's Green Stage.<ref name=britton>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/84484|last=Britton|first=Luke Morgan|title=Teenager Declan McKenna wins Glastonbury's Emerging Talent Competition|work=[[NME]]|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' called him \"one of the most sought-after new acts\" in the United Kingdom after his win,<ref name=milton>{{cite news|url=http://diymag.com/2015/10/29/the-astounding-early-days-of-declan-mckenna|last=Milton|first=Jamie|title=The astounding early days of Declan McKenna|work=DIY|date=29 October 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> shortly after McKenna signed a management contract with Q Prime (the management company that represents British indie rock band [[Foals (band)|Foals]], amongst others).<ref name=wilkinson/> More than 40 record companies vied to sign him, with McKenna choosing [[Columbia Records]].<ref name=\"welch\" />\n\nMcKenna wrote an extensive number of demo songs prior to releasing his first breakout single. He described the music as \"Not very good!\" and told an interviewer that he was trying to imitate [[Sufjan Stevens]] using basic music software. He posted roughly two albums' worth of material on his web site, but took them down after August 2015.<ref name=savage>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Mark|title=Declan McKenna: Bringing back the protest song (without being a bore)|work=BBC News|date=13 April 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39526472}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, McKenna self-released his first single, \"Brazil\". It was originally released through his own [[YouTube]] channel on December 2, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=39r0QFD1oPM |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Brazil |date=December 2, 2014 |website=[[YouTube]] |access-date=August 17, 2017}}</ref> The song criticised [[FIFA]], the [[Sport governing body|governing body]] of [[association football]], for awarding the [[FIFA World Cup]] to [[Brazil]] in 2014 without addressing the extensive and deep poverty affecting the people of the nation.<ref name=milton /> McKenna later told ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' that he wrote the song because \"it's politics and what I see in the news, and it's just general things I feel strongly about, things happening in my life.\"<ref name=milton /> \"Brazil\" garnered McKenna widespread attention, as many sports commentators found the song to be a commentary on the emerging [[2015 FIFA corruption case|FIFA corruption scandal]]. (Ironically, McKenna's single \"Isombard\" appeared on the soundtrack for the 2016 [[Association football|football]] video game ''[[FIFA 17]]''.) Later in the year, he was interviewed on [[Sky News]] to discuss his views on football's relationship with poverty.<ref name=\"welch\" /><ref name=milton /> \"Brazil\" reached number one on the Alt 18 Countdown for 23 January 2016 on the Alt Nation alternative rock radio station on [[Sirius XM Radio]],<ref name=altnationjan23>{{cite web|url=http://blog.siriusxm.com/2016/01/25/declan-mckenna-top-the-alt-18-with-brazil-12316/|last=Sam|first=Doric|title=Declan McKenna top the Alt 18 with Brazil (1/23/16)|website=Sirius XM|date=25 January 2016|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> and repeated as number one a week later, on 30 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.siriusxm.com/2016/02/01/declan-mckenna-top-the-alt-18-with-brazil-13016/|last=Sam|first=Doric|title=Declan McKenna top the Alt 18 with Brazil (1/30/16)|website=Sirius XM|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===First EPs and ''What Do You Think About the Car?'' (2015\u20132018)===\n[[File:Declan McKenna, Boileroom, Guildford (27600255570).jpg|thumb|right|200px|McKenna in 2016, performing at the Boileroom in [[Guildford]]]]\nDeclan McKenna spent the remaining months of 2015 playing a wide range of British and Irish music festivals and concerts in venues throughout London.<ref name=king>{{cite news|url=http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/SOMERSAULT-Saturday-lineup/story-27471467-detail/story.html#ixzz3whDoAEPk|last=King|first=Ruth|title=Somersault Festival: Saturday line-up|work=North Devon Journal|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814062821/http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/SOMERSAULT-Saturday-lineup/story-27471467-detail/story.html#ixzz3whDoAEPk|archive-date=14 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He played the Somersault Festival in [[North Devon]], England, in July;<ref name=king /> the Boston Big Gig festival in [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[Lincolnshire]], in July;<ref>{{cite news|title=Big plans ahead for Big Gig 2017|work=Boston Standard|date=30 January 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016|url=http://www.bostonstandard.co.uk/what-s-on/arts-leisure/big-plans-ahead-for-big-gig-2017-1-7188605}}</ref> the [[Electric Picnic]] music festival in [[Stradbally]], [[County Laois]], Ireland, in September,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/whats-on/music/electric-picnic-2015-stage-times-6355239|last=Hynes|first=Robert|title=Electric Picnic 2015: Stage times announced for this weekend's festival|work=Irish Mirror|date=31 August 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and the Mirrors music festival in London in October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://diymag.com/2015/10/28/traams-share-their-brief-guide-to-2000s-indie-revival-live-favourites-that-never-made-the-album-playlist|title=Mirrors Festival: TRAAMS share their 'Brief Guide to 2000s Indie Revival Live Favourites That Never Made the Album' playlist|work=DIY|date=28 October 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, following the success of \"Brazil\" and his shows in London, McKenna self-released his second single, \"Paracetamol\". The five-and-a-half minute song discussed how [[transgender]] teenagers are misrepresented in the media.<ref name=\"welch\" /> In an interview with Sound of Boston, McKenna explained that the title of the song came from \"the idea of using the lyric [[paracetamol]] was a way of comparing the belief that someone can be cured from who they are, via therapy, to an everyday painkiller.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bedian|first1=Knar|title=Interview: Declan McKenna|url=http://soundofboston.com/interview-declan-mckenna/|website=Sound of Boston}}</ref> Matt Wilkinson of ''NME'' called \"Paracetamol\" McKenna's second break-out hit. Although it was not likely to receive radio airplay or top out the charts, Wilkinson argued, the song showed that McKenna was not just another \"UK indie troubadour, a little bit oikish and with a nifty talent for mainstream melody\", but rather a solid and accomplished songwriter who can deliver \"bruised and vulnerable\" vocals.<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons of the music Web site ThisNewBand.com said the song showed a maturity that clearly indicated McKenna was not \"just a teen dream or a one hit wonder.\"<ref name=lyons /> ''Billboard'' said in early 2016 that McKenna was \"making inroads in America\" with \"Brazil\", which charted on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Alternative Songs chart (for the week ending 27 February 2016) at number 32, rising to number 26 on the 5 March 2016 chart.<ref name=\"caulfield\">{{cite news|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Tomorrow's Hits: She Is We, Declan McKenna & Colours|work=Billboard|date=4 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6897346/tomorrows-hits-she-is-we-declan-mckenna-colours}}</ref>\n\nMcKenna stayed quiet for much of 2016, writing songs in his bedroom for his debut album,<ref name=smithinterviewed>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Thomas|title=Declan McKenna Interviewed: \u2018A Lot Of People Don\u2019t Understand How Intelligent Young People Are\u2019|work=NME|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=2 January 2018|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/declan-mckenna-interviewewd-a-lot-of-people-don-t-understand-how-intelligent-young-people-are-3702}}</ref> but released \"Bethlehem\" that year, and in late August, his fourth single, \"Isombard\", which treated right-wing media.<ref name=\"smythz\" /> He played at several music festivals in England: the [[NME Awards]] in February 2016;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/nme-awards-shows-2016-revealed/#sthash.OyPMDQan.dpuf|last=Bargiela|first=Sarah|title=NME Awards Shows 2016 revealed|work=Entertainment Focus|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> the [[Live at Leeds (festival)|Live at Leeds]] festival over the 2016 [[May Day]] [[bank holiday]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Live at Leeds line-up revealed|work=Yorkshire Evening Post|date=28 January 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/top-stories/live-at-leeds-line-up-revealed-1-7703057}}</ref> [[The Great Escape Festival]] in [[Brighton and Hove]], [[East Sussex]], in May 2016;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/read/dilly-dally-tuff-love-among-first-confirmations-great-escape/|last=Taylor|first=Sam|title=Dilly Dally and Tuff Love among first confirmations for The Great Escape|work=Upset Magazine|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125033807/http://www.upsetmagazine.com/read/dilly-dally-tuff-love-among-first-confirmations-great-escape/|archive-date=25 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[Standon Calling]] festival in late July 2016 in [[Standon, Hertfordshire|Standon]], Hertfordshire;<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything Everything, Suede, Swim Deep to play Standon Calling 2016|work=DIY|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://diymag.com/2016/03/01/everything-everything-suede-swim-deep-to-play-standon-calling-2016}}</ref> and the [[Field Day (festival)|Field Day]] music festival in London in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://crackmagazine.net/events/news-posts/first-acts-announced-for-field-day-2016/|title=First acts announced for Field Day 2016|work=Crack Magazine|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> He made his North American debut at [[Jannus Live]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], [[Florida]], on 11 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cridlin|first=Jay|title=The Struts, Front Bottoms set free concert at Jannus Live in St. Petersburg|work=Tampa Bay Tribune|date=16 February 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/soundcheck/the-struts-front-bottoms-set-free-concert-at-jannus-live-in-st-petersburg/2265538|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310074400/http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/soundcheck/the-struts-front-bottoms-set-free-concert-at-jannus-live-in-st-petersburg/2265538|archive-date=10 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He then played three sets<ref name=\"caulfield\" /> at [[South by Southwest|South by Southwest Music]] on 15 March 2016.\n<ref>{{cite news|last=Graff|first=Gary|title=Naughty by Nature, Jenny Lewis & More Lined Up for Rachael Ray's SXSW Feedback Party: Exclusive|work=Billboard|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/6913520/naughty-by-nature-jenny-lewis-rachael-ray-feedback-sxsw}}</ref> In October 2016, he was confirmed to play at the 31st edition of [[Eurosonic Noorderslag]] in [[Groningen]], Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|title = First European Artists Confirmed for Eurosonic Noorderslag \u2013 Eurosonic Noorderslag |url = https://www.eurosonic-noorderslag.nl/en/news/festival/article/eurosonic-noorderslag-bevestigt-26-acts/|website = Eurosonic Noorderslag|accessdate = 26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Declan McKenna on stage at TRNSMT, Glasgow Green (geograph 5833560).jpg|thumb|left|McKenna on stage with guitarist Isabel Torres at [[TRNSMT]] in [[Glasgow]], 2018]]\nMcKenna appeared on [[BBC Music]]'s \"Sound of 2017\" list at the end of 2016, after releasing the two EPs ''Stains'' and ''Liar'' that year.<ref name=\"smythz\" /> The EPs had similar tracklists, with \"Brazil\" and \"Paracetamol\" appearing on both. McKenna would release two more singles, \"The Kids Don't Wanna Come Home\" and \"Humongous\", before releasing his debut album, titled ''[[What Do You Think About the Car?]]'' English musician, record producer and composer [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]], who had produced albums by [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Depeche Mode]], and [[Florence and the Machine]], produced the album, which was recorded at a [[Kensal Green]] recording studio. The album was released on 21 July 2017 and received generally positive reviews. It featured all six of McKenna's previously released singles, as well as five new tracks. All songs on the album were written by McKenna alone, with the exception of \"Listen to Your Friends\", which was co-written with [[Rostam Batmanglij]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/what-do-you-think-about-the-car/id1208110183|title=What Do You Think About the Car? (2017)|publisher=iTunes|access-date=12 April 2017}}</ref> McKenna played at various festivals in 2017, including [[Coachella Festival|Coachella]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coachella.com/lineup |title=Lineup |publisher=Coachella |date= |accessdate=1 April 2017 |url-status= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320040746/https://www.coachella.com/lineup/ |archive-date=20 March 2017 |df= }}</ref> [[Lollapalooza]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/kot/ct-lollapalooza-2017-lineup-20170322-column.html|title=Lollapalooza 2017: Chance the Rapper, Lorde, Arcade Fire top 170-band lineup|date=22 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> [[Glastonbury Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39447179/declan-mckenna-and-alt-j-on-living-up-to-the-glastonbury-wow-factor|title=Declan McKenna and Alt J on living up to the Glastonbury 'wow-factor'|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> and [[Reading and Leeds Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfestival.com/line-up/poster|title=Line Up Poster|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=7 April 2017|publisher=[[Reading and Leeds Festival]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413235607/http://www.readingfestival.com/line-up/poster|archive-date=13 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, McKenna won the [[BBC Music Awards|BBC Music Award]] for [[BBC Introducing]] Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Music Awards 2017 announce Declan McKenna as BBC Music Introducing Artist Of The Year|work=BBC|date=6 December 2017|accessdate=2 January 2018|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/bbc-music-introducing-declan-mckenna}}</ref> He also appeared at the Pilton Party 2017 with [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]].<ref>http://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/information/pilton-party-2017</ref> On 17 January 2018 McKenna released a music video for \"Make Me Your Queen\".\n\n===''Zeros'' (2019\u2013present)===\n\nOn 19 August 2019, McKenna released the song \"British Bombs\", which criticises UK foreign policy. He stated that it is specifically about \"the hypocrisy of the British arms trade and the weapons convention in London\". He wrote it as a result of wanting to write a song directly addressing war.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/declan-mc-kenna-opens-up-politically-charged-new-single-british-bombs-2539718 |title=Exclusive \u2013 Declan McKenna opens up about his politically charged new single 'British Bombs' |last=Aubrey |first=Elizabeth |date=19 August 2019 |website=[[NME]] |access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> McKenna later announced via [[Twitter]] on 18 December that his upcoming second studio album was mastered and ready for release. He also had an artwork shoot for the album on the same day.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1207381266812801024 |user=DeclanMcKenna |title=album is mastered and ready. artwork shoot today went hard. holy crapola. she\u2019s alive. happy holidays x |author=Declan McKenna |date=18 December 2019 |access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> On 29 January 2020, McKenna revealed that his second album would be titled ''Zeros'' and be released on 15 May 2020. However, due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|COVID-19 outbreak]], he postponed the album from its original release date of 24 March 2020 to be released on 21 August 2020. He also released the song \"Beautiful Faces\" as the album's lead single.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://diymag.com/2020/01/30/declan-mckenna-new-album-zeros-watch-new-video-beautiful-people |title=Declan McKenna announces new album 'Zeroes' |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nMcKenna writes his own songs, but is supported by a band on tour currently consisting of Isabel Torres (''guitarist''), Nathan Cox (''keys''), William Bishop (''bass'') and Gabrielle Marie King (''drummer'')<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHocldC9C8g&ab_channel=DeclanUpdated</ref>,  although he has previously played all of his own instruments.<ref name=brinsford /> In terms of the development of his musical style, he says he would most like to emulate [[David Bowie]]'s career.<ref name=savage />\n\n[[BBC News]] called \"Brazil\" an extraordinarily mature song for a 16-year-old songwriter.<ref name=bbc /> Matt Wilkinson at ''NME'' called it \"one of the best songs\" of 2015, and had high praise for McKenna's second single, \"Paracetamol\", as well.<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons of ThisNewBand.com called \"Brazil\" \"a catchy song no doubt\", and also noted that it was \"a sharp critique on sports, money and power.\"<ref name=lyons>{{cite web|url=http://thisnewband.com/837/meet-16-year-old-declan-mckenna-and-his-incredible-song-brazil/|last=Lyons|first=Jon|title=Meet 16-Year-Old Declan McKenna and His Incredible Song \"Brazil\"|website=ThisNewBand.com|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107100125/http://thisnewband.com/837/meet-16-year-old-declan-mckenna-and-his-incredible-song-brazil/|archive-date=7 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSome music critics have tempered their praise of McKenna. Matt Wilkinson called McKenna's London gigs surprisingly good, if \"rough around the edges\".<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons has observed that as of November 2015, McKenna's songs seemed to indicate an artist still experimenting with bands and styles of music which have influenced him. He felt McKenna was still \"searching for his own sound right in front of the crowd. An artist is being born note by note.\"<ref name=lyons /> Andy Welch, music critic for the ''[[Bristol Post]]'', said McKenna was \"one to watch\", displaying \"lots of early, ragged promise\".<ref name=\"welch\" /> Grammy winning singer Adele commented in an interview \"He's so talented. I praise him for work so hard and doing so well at such a young age.\"\n\nAndre Paine of the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' was less impressed with McKenna's live show, commenting that although his performance \"had plenty of energy ... [he] didn't quite live up to his reputation as the voice of a generation\", going on to call McKenna's performance \"messy\".<ref name=Paine>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/declan-mckenna-tour-review-not-quite-the-voice-of-a-generation-a3547376.html|last=Paine|first=Andre |title= Declan McKenna, tour review: Not quite the voice of a generation|website=Standard.co.uk|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> Liam Gallagher has also been critical of McKenna's music, commenting that it was simply \"not for me\".<ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=Liam Gallagher's Weekly Music Corner Ep. 3 (HBO)|date=2017-10-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZqZa3-24Gro|accessdate=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcKenna acknowledges that he is seen as a \"political\" or \"protest\" singer. He does not see himself as someone \"leading the conversation\" but rather as a person singing about things his peers are already talking about.<ref name=smithinterviewed /> For much of his initial work, McKenna said he tried to find inspiration for lyrics and topics in his private life. He felt his own life to be so uneventful, however, that he turned to political and social issues which he felt needed to be discussed.<ref name=savage /> For his second album, however, McKenna feels that he has had so much happen that he can draw on more personal experiences for his lyrics.<ref name=norris>{{cite news|last=Norris|first=John|title=With Politics, Eye Makeup and That Album Cover, Declan McKenna Goes Bold|work=Billboard|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7905012/declan-mckenna-politics-interview}}</ref>\n\nMcKenna says he feels good about being a role model.<ref name=smithinterviewed /> At first, he said he also struggled to understand both the criticism and praise he received, but has been able to be more mature and more analytical about both.<ref name=norris />\n\nAfter adopting a somewhat [[glam rock]] visual style for his live performances (which included extensive use of eye makeup and [[glitter]]),<ref name=savage /> McKenna addressed questions about his sexuality with ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'' magazine by declining to label himself. \"I'm young. I'm here to be experimented with\", he said, and told the interviewer that he is \"learning about a lot of things\". He was not being coy, he said, just honest about where he was in his life.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Declan McKenna On Ditching Labels: 'I'm Here to Be Experimented With'|work=Attitude|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://attitude.co.uk/article/singer-declan-mckenna-on-ditching-labels-im-here-to-be-experimented-with/15173/}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/49073/declan-mckenna/ |title=Declan McKenna : full Official Charts history |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(FL)]]<br/><ref name=\"BEL FL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Declan+McKenna |title=Discografie Declan McKenna |website=[[Ultratop]] |language=Dutch |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/irish-albums-chart/20170728/ie7502/ |title=Official Irish Albums Chart Top 50 : 28 July 2017 \u2013 03 August 2017 |date=28 July 2017 |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official Charts Company|SCO]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20170728/40/ |title=Official Scottish Albums Chart Top 100 : 28 July 2017 \u2013 03 August 2017 |date=28 July 2017 |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br/>Heat]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/heatseekers-albums |title=Heatseekers Albums Chart |website=Billboard |access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Tribes''\n|\n* Released: March 1, 2014\n* Labels: Independent\n* Format: Digital download\n| \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''I've Made It Further Than You (No, Not You)''\n|\n* Released: July 12, 2014\n* Labels: Independent\n* Format: Digital download\n| \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013 || \u2013\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''[[What Do You Think About the Car?]]''\n|\n* Release: 21 July 2017\n* Labels: [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n* Formats: [[Compact disc|CD]], [[LP record|LP]], [[Music download|download]], [[Music streaming|streaming]]\n| 11 || 130 || 26 || 8 || 7\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Zeros''\n|\n* To be released: 21 August 2020\n* Label: Columbia\n* Formats: TBA\n| colspan=\"12\" {{TBA|To be released}}\n|}\n\n===Extended plays===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of extended plays\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Details\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Stains''\n|\n* Released: March 4, 2016\n* Label: Because Music\n* Format: CD, LP, streaming\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Liar''\n|\n* Released: May 20, 2016\n* Label: High Quality Popular Music\n* Format: Download, streaming\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| ''Regurgitated''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://recordstoreday.co.uk/releases/rsd-2019/declan-mckenna/|title=Declan McKenna - Record Store Day|website=recordstoreday.co.uk|accessdate=23 April 2019}}</ref>\n|\n* Released: April 13, 2019\n* Label: Columbia\n* Format: 10\" [[Phonograph record|vinyl]]\n|-\n|}\n\n===Singles===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of singles, with selected chart positions, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:18em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:1em;\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"7\"| Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(FL)]]<br/><ref name=\"BEL FL\"/>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Syndicat National de l'\u00c9dition Phonographique|FRA]]<br /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://lescharts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Declan+Mckenna |title=Discographie Declan McKenna |website=lescharts.com |language=French |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Billboard Japan Hot 100|JPN]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/japan-hot-100 |title=Japan Hot 100 Chart |website=Billboard |access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Mexico Ingles Airplay|MEX]]<br><ref name=MEX>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/mexico-ingles-airplay |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Mexico Ingles Airplay chart history |website=Billboard |access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Adult album alternative|US<br />AAA]]<br /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/AAA|title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Adult Alternative Songs chart history |website=Billboard |access-date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Alternative Songs|US<br />Alt.]]<br /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/MRT |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Alternative Songs chart history |website=Billboard |access-date=19 February 2020}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Rock Songs|US<br />Rock]]<br /><ref name=\"hot-rock-songs\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/rock-songs |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Rock Songs chart history |website=Billboard |access-date=27 September 2019}}</ref>\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Brazil\"\n| rowspan=\"2\"| 2015\n| \u2014 || 135 || 45 || \u2014 || 12 || 16 || 41\n| rowspan=\"9\"| ''What Do You Think About the Car?''\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Paracetamol\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Bethlehem\"\n| rowspan=\"3\"| 2016\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Isombard\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"The Kids Don't Wanna Come Home\"\n| 84 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Humongous\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2017\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 44 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Why Do You Feel So Down?\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Make Me Your Queen\"\n| rowspan=\"2\" | 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Listen to Your Friends\"\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"British Bombs\"\n| 2019\n| 94 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| {{n/a|Non-album single}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | \"Beautiful Faces\"\n| 2020\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014 || 23 || 24 || \u2014{{efn-ua|\"Beautiful Faces\" did not chart on the [[Rock Songs|Hot Rock Songs]] chart but did peak at number 42 on the [[Rock Airplay]] chart.<ref name=\"Rock-Air\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.billboard.com/music/declan-mckenna/chart-history/RKA |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Rock Airplay chart history |website=Billboard |access-date=18 February 2020}}</ref>}}\n| ''Zeros''\n|-\n| colspan=\"14\" style=\"font-size:85%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a recording that did not chart or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n===Guest appearances===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\"| Year\n! scope=\"col\"| Album\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"In Blue\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/moominvalley-official-soundtrack/1453752386|title=MOOMINVALLEY (Official Soundtrack) by Various Artists|date=19 April 2019|accessdate=26 February 2019}}</ref>\n| 2019\n| ''[[Moominvalley (TV series)#Music|MOOMINVALLEY (Official Soundtrack)]]''\n|-\n|}\n\n===Notes===\n{{notelist-ua}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Declan McKenna}}\n*[https://www.declanmckenna.net Official website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McKenna, Declan}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cheshunt]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:English child singers]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:English rock pianists]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records artists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:21st-century pianists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:21st-century guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male pianists]]\n[[Category:21st-century male singers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English singer-songwriter and musician (born 1998)}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- Individual -->\n| name             = Declan McKenna\n| image            = Declan McKenna, Patterns, Brighton (Great Escape 2018) (40780741260) (cropped).jpg\n| alt              = \n| caption          = McKenna at [[The Great Escape Festival]] 2018\n| landscape        = \n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Declan Benedict McKenna\n| birth_place      = [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[Greater London]], England\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1998|12|24|df=y}}\n| origin           = \n| instrument       = {{hlist|Vocals|guitar|keyboards|mandolin}}\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|Singer|songwriter|musician}}\n| years_active     = 2014\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[Columbia Records|Columbia]]|High Quality Popular Music}}\n| associated_acts  = Superfood, Feet, Etchells, Zimmo, Scors, [[Osquello]], [[Clairo]] \n| website          = {{URL|www.declanmckenna.net/}}\n}}\n\n'''Declan Benedict McKenna'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mobile.ascap.com/aceclient/AceWeb/#ace/writer/808716719/MCKENNA%20DECLAN%20BENEDICT|title=ASCAP Ace Search|last=McKenna|first=Declan Benedict|publisher=[[American Society of Composers, Authors and Publishers]] (ASCAP)|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> (born 24 December 1998) is an English singer, songwriter, and musician. He initially gained recognition for winning the [[Glastonbury Festival]]'s Emerging Talent Competition in 2015. McKenna self-released the song \"Brazil\", a protest song criticising [[FIFA]] and the [[2014 FIFA World Cup]] held in Brazil, as his debut single in December 2014. It gained recognition after its re-release in August 2015. It reached number one on [[Sirius XM Radio]]'s [[Alt Nation]] Alt 18 Countdown for 23 January 2016 and held that spot for three weeks. The song also reached number 16 on the U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs]] chart, number 45 in Japan and number 135 in France. His popularity attracted the attention of many major music labels; he eventually signed to [[Columbia Records]] in 2016.\n\nMcKenna continued to write and record music for his debut studio album during 2016. During this time, he also performed concerts and appeared at festivals. He released ''[[What Do You Think About the Car?]]'' through Columbia on 21 July 2017. Songs that appear on the album that were released as singles prior to the album\u2019s release include \"Paracetamol\", \"Isombard\" and \"The Kids Don't Wanna Come Home\", which peaked at number 84 on Belgium's [[Ultratop|Ultratop Flanders]] chart. Also during 2017, he made appearances at the [[Coachella Valley Music and Arts Festival|Coachella]] and [[Lollapalooza]] festivals.\n\n==Life and career==\n===Early life and breakout with \"Brazil\" (1998\u20132015)===\nDeclan McKenna was born in [[London Borough of Enfield|Enfield]], [[Greater London]],<ref>https://search.findmypast.co.uk/results/world-records/england-and-wales-births-1837-2006?firstname=declan%20&lastname=mckenna&eventyear=1998&eventyear_offset=1</ref> on 24 December 1998<ref name=\"welch\" /><ref name=smythz>{{cite news|last=Smyth|first=David|title=Declan McKenna, interview: The voice of Generation Z|work=The Evening Standard|date=6 January 2017|accessdate=6 January 2017|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/declan-mckenna-interview-the-voice-of-generation-z-a3434331.html}}</ref> and grew up in [[Cheshunt]], [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=\"wilkinson\">{{cite news|title=New Music of the Day: Declan McKenna \u2013 Paracetamol|last=Wilkinson|first=Matt|date=22 November 2015|work=[[NME]]}}</ref> where he attended [[St Mary's Church of England High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hertfordshiremercury.co.uk/Waltham-Cross-summer-fair-provides-eclectic-entertainment-SLIDESHOW/story-21986168-detail/story.html#8|title=Waltham Cross summer fair provides eclectic entertainment: Slideshow|work=Hertfordshire Mercury|date=7 June 2014|accessdate=8 January 2016}}{{Dead link|date=July 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He began taking his [[General Certificate of Secondary Education|GCSE]] exams in the summer of 2015.<ref name=\"welch\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Glastonbury-Festival-competition-winner-Declan/story-28341626-detail/story.html |title=Glastonbury Festival competition winner Declan McKenna is one to watch |last=Welch |first=Andy |date=12 December 2015 |work=Bristol Post |access-date=8 January 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151220113233/http://www.bristolpost.co.uk/Glastonbury-Festival-competition-winner-Declan/story-28341626-detail/story.html |archive-date=20 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=bbc /> He later studied for his [[GCE Advanced Level (United Kingdom)|A-levels]] in English literature, Philosophy and Ethics, and Sociology, but stopped after a few months after his music career began to consume too much of his time.<ref name=smythz />\n\nIn 2015, McKenna entered the Glastonbury Festival's Emerging Talent Competition. The festival named him the winner of the contest in April 2015,<ref name=bbc>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p02v4y9m|title=New Talent at Glastonbury|work=BBC News|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref><ref name=brinsford>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/james-brinsford/why-glastonbury-2015-will_b_7065156.html|last=Brinsford|first=Brinsford|title=10 Reasons Why Glastonbury 2015 May Be the Greatest Show on Earth|work=Huffington Post|date=17 April 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> for which he was awarded a \u00a35,000 prize and a slot on the festival's William's Green Stage.<ref name=britton>{{cite news|url=http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/84484|last=Britton|first=Luke Morgan|title=Teenager Declan McKenna wins Glastonbury's Emerging Talent Competition|work=[[NME]]|date=13 April 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> ''[[NME]]'' called him \"one of the most sought-after new acts\" in the United Kingdom after his win,<ref name=milton>{{cite news|url=http://diymag.com/2015/10/29/the-astounding-early-days-of-declan-mckenna|last=Milton|first=Jamie|title=The astounding early days of Declan McKenna|work=DIY|date=29 October 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> shortly after McKenna signed a management contract with Q Prime (the management company that represents British indie rock band [[Foals (band)|Foals]], amongst others).<ref name=wilkinson/> More than 40 record companies vied to sign him, with McKenna choosing [[Columbia Records]].<ref name=\"welch\" />\n\nMcKenna wrote an extensive number of demo songs prior to releasing his first breakout single. He described the music as \"Not very good!\" and told an interviewer that he was trying to imitate [[Sufjan Stevens]] using basic music software. He posted roughly two albums' worth of material on his web site, but took them down after August 2015.<ref name=savage>{{cite news|last=Savage|first=Mark|title=Declan McKenna: Bringing back the protest song (without being a bore)|work=BBC News|date=13 April 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-39526472}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, McKenna self-released his first single, \"Brazil\". It was originally released through his own [[YouTube]] channel on December 2, 2014.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=39r0QFD1oPM |title=Declan McKenna \u2013 Brazil |date=December 2, 2014 |website=[[YouTube]] |access-date=August 17, 2017}}</ref> The song criticised [[FIFA]], the [[Sport governing body|governing body]] of [[association football]], for awarding the [[FIFA World Cup]] to [[Brazil]] in 2014 without addressing the extensive and deep poverty affecting the people of the nation.<ref name=milton /> McKenna later told ''[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]]'' that he wrote the song because \"it's politics and what I see in the news, and it's just general things I feel strongly about, things happening in my life.\"<ref name=milton /> \"Brazil\" garnered McKenna widespread attention, as many sports commentators found the song to be a commentary on the emerging [[2015 FIFA corruption case|FIFA corruption scandal]]. (Ironically, McKenna's single \"Isombard\" appeared on the soundtrack for the 2016 [[Association football|football]] video game ''[[FIFA 17]]''.) Later in the year, he was interviewed on [[Sky News]] to discuss his views on football's relationship with poverty.<ref name=\"welch\" /><ref name=milton /> \"Brazil\" reached number one on the Alt 18 Countdown for 23 January 2016 on the Alt Nation alternative rock radio station on [[Sirius XM Radio]],<ref name=altnationjan23>{{cite web|url=http://blog.siriusxm.com/2016/01/25/declan-mckenna-top-the-alt-18-with-brazil-12316/|last=Sam|first=Doric|title=Declan McKenna top the Alt 18 with Brazil (1/23/16)|website=Sirius XM|date=25 January 2016|accessdate=29 January 2016}}</ref> and repeated as number one a week later, on 30 January.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.siriusxm.com/2016/02/01/declan-mckenna-top-the-alt-18-with-brazil-13016/|last=Sam|first=Doric|title=Declan McKenna top the Alt 18 with Brazil (1/30/16)|website=Sirius XM|date=1 February 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n===First EPs and ''What Do You Think About the Car?'' (2015\u20132018)===\n[[File:Declan McKenna, Boileroom, Guildford (27600255570).jpg|thumb|right|200px|McKenna in 2016, performing at the Boileroom in [[Guildford]]]]\nDeclan McKenna spent the remaining months of 2015 playing a wide range of British and Irish music festivals and concerts in venues throughout London.<ref name=king>{{cite news|url=http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/SOMERSAULT-Saturday-lineup/story-27471467-detail/story.html#ixzz3whDoAEPk|last=King|first=Ruth|title=Somersault Festival: Saturday line-up|work=North Devon Journal|date=23 July 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150814062821/http://www.northdevonjournal.co.uk/SOMERSAULT-Saturday-lineup/story-27471467-detail/story.html#ixzz3whDoAEPk|archive-date=14 August 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> He played the Somersault Festival in [[North Devon]], England, in July;<ref name=king /> the Boston Big Gig festival in [[Boston, Lincolnshire|Boston]], [[Lincolnshire]], in July;<ref>{{cite news|title=Big plans ahead for Big Gig 2017|work=Boston Standard|date=30 January 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016|url=http://www.bostonstandard.co.uk/what-s-on/arts-leisure/big-plans-ahead-for-big-gig-2017-1-7188605}}</ref> the [[Electric Picnic]] music festival in [[Stradbally]], [[County Laois]], Ireland, in September,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishmirror.ie/whats-on/music/electric-picnic-2015-stage-times-6355239|last=Hynes|first=Robert|title=Electric Picnic 2015: Stage times announced for this weekend's festival|work=Irish Mirror|date=31 August 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> and the Mirrors music festival in London in October.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://diymag.com/2015/10/28/traams-share-their-brief-guide-to-2000s-indie-revival-live-favourites-that-never-made-the-album-playlist|title=Mirrors Festival: TRAAMS share their 'Brief Guide to 2000s Indie Revival Live Favourites That Never Made the Album' playlist|work=DIY|date=28 October 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2015, following the success of \"Brazil\" and his shows in London, McKenna self-released his second single, \"Paracetamol\". The five-and-a-half minute song discussed how [[transgender]] teenagers are misrepresented in the media.<ref name=\"welch\" /> In an interview with Sound of Boston, McKenna explained that the title of the song came from \"the idea of using the lyric [[paracetamol]] was a way of comparing the belief that someone can be cured from who they are, via therapy, to an everyday painkiller.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bedian|first1=Knar|title=Interview: Declan McKenna|url=http://soundofboston.com/interview-declan-mckenna/|website=Sound of Boston}}</ref> Matt Wilkinson of ''NME'' called \"Paracetamol\" McKenna's second break-out hit. Although it was not likely to receive radio airplay or top out the charts, Wilkinson argued, the song showed that McKenna was not just another \"UK indie troubadour, a little bit oikish and with a nifty talent for mainstream melody\", but rather a solid and accomplished songwriter who can deliver \"bruised and vulnerable\" vocals.<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons of the music Web site ThisNewBand.com said the song showed a maturity that clearly indicated McKenna was not \"just a teen dream or a one hit wonder.\"<ref name=lyons /> ''Billboard'' said in early 2016 that McKenna was \"making inroads in America\" with \"Brazil\", which charted on ''Billboard''<nowiki/>'s Alternative Songs chart (for the week ending 27 February 2016) at number 32, rising to number 26 on the 5 March 2016 chart.<ref name=\"caulfield\">{{cite news|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|title=Tomorrow's Hits: She Is We, Declan McKenna & Colours|work=Billboard|date=4 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/6897346/tomorrows-hits-she-is-we-declan-mckenna-colours}}</ref>\n\nMcKenna stayed quiet for much of 2016, writing songs in his bedroom for his debut album,<ref name=smithinterviewed>{{cite news|last=Smith|first=Thomas|title=Declan McKenna Interviewed: \u2018A Lot Of People Don\u2019t Understand How Intelligent Young People Are\u2019|work=NME|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=2 January 2018|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-radar/declan-mckenna-interviewewd-a-lot-of-people-don-t-understand-how-intelligent-young-people-are-3702}}</ref> but released \"Bethlehem\" that year, and in late August, his fourth single, \"Isombard\", which treated right-wing media.<ref name=\"smythz\" /> He played at several music festivals in England: the [[NME Awards]] in February 2016;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.entertainment-focus.com/music-section/music-news/nme-awards-shows-2016-revealed/#sthash.OyPMDQan.dpuf|last=Bargiela|first=Sarah|title=NME Awards Shows 2016 revealed|work=Entertainment Focus|date=1 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> the [[Live at Leeds (festival)|Live at Leeds]] festival over the 2016 [[May Day]] [[bank holiday]];<ref>{{cite news|title=Live at Leeds line-up revealed|work=Yorkshire Evening Post|date=28 January 2016|accessdate=10 February 2016|url=http://www.yorkshireeveningpost.co.uk/news/latest-news/top-stories/live-at-leeds-line-up-revealed-1-7703057}}</ref> [[The Great Escape Festival]] in [[Brighton and Hove]], [[East Sussex]], in May 2016;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.upsetmagazine.com/read/dilly-dally-tuff-love-among-first-confirmations-great-escape/|last=Taylor|first=Sam|title=Dilly Dally and Tuff Love among first confirmations for The Great Escape|work=Upset Magazine|date=2 December 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160125033807/http://www.upsetmagazine.com/read/dilly-dally-tuff-love-among-first-confirmations-great-escape/|archive-date=25 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> the [[Standon Calling]] festival in late July 2016 in [[Standon, Hertfordshire|Standon]], Hertfordshire;<ref>{{cite news|title=Everything Everything, Suede, Swim Deep to play Standon Calling 2016|work=DIY|date=1 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://diymag.com/2016/03/01/everything-everything-suede-swim-deep-to-play-standon-calling-2016}}</ref> and the [[Field Day (festival)|Field Day]] music festival in London in June 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://crackmagazine.net/events/news-posts/first-acts-announced-for-field-day-2016/|title=First acts announced for Field Day 2016|work=Crack Magazine|date=26 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016}}</ref> He made his North American debut at [[Jannus Live]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], [[Florida]], on 11 March 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cridlin|first=Jay|title=The Struts, Front Bottoms set free concert at Jannus Live in St. Petersburg|work=Tampa Bay Tribune|date=16 February 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/soundcheck/the-struts-front-bottoms-set-free-concert-at-jannus-live-in-st-petersburg/2265538|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310074400/http://www.tampabay.com/blogs/soundcheck/the-struts-front-bottoms-set-free-concert-at-jannus-live-in-st-petersburg/2265538|archive-date=10 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> He then played three sets<ref name=\"caulfield\" /> at [[South by Southwest|South by Southwest Music]] on 15 March 2016.\n<ref>{{cite news|last=Graff|first=Gary|title=Naughty by Nature, Jenny Lewis & More Lined Up for Rachael Ray's SXSW Feedback Party: Exclusive|work=Billboard|date=9 March 2016|accessdate=9 March 2016|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/events/sxsw/6913520/naughty-by-nature-jenny-lewis-rachael-ray-feedback-sxsw}}</ref> In October 2016, he was confirmed to play at the 31st edition of [[Eurosonic Noorderslag]] in [[Groningen]], Netherlands.<ref>{{Cite web|title = First European Artists Confirmed for Eurosonic Noorderslag \u2013 Eurosonic Noorderslag |url = https://www.eurosonic-noorderslag.nl/en/news/festival/article/eurosonic-noorderslag-bevestigt-26-acts/|website = Eurosonic Noorderslag|accessdate = 26 October 2016}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Declan McKenna on stage at TRNSMT, Glasgow Green (geograph 5833560).jpg|thumb|left|McKenna on stage with guitarist Isabel Torres at [[TRNSMT]] in [[Glasgow]], 2018]]\nMcKenna appeared on [[BBC Music]]'s \"Sound of 2017\" list at the end of 2016, after releasing the two EPs ''Stains'' and ''Liar'' that year.<ref name=\"smythz\" /> The EPs had similar tracklists, with \"Brazil\" and \"Paracetamol\" appearing on both. McKenna would release two more singles, \"The Kids Don't Wanna Come Home\" and \"Humongous\", before releasing his debut album, titled ''[[What Do You Think About the Car?]]'' English musician, record producer and composer [[James Ford (musician)|James Ford]], who had produced albums by [[Arctic Monkeys]], [[Depeche Mode]], and [[Florence and the Machine]], produced the album, which was recorded at a [[Kensal Green]] recording studio. The album was released on 21 July 2017 and received generally positive reviews. It featured all six of McKenna's previously released singles, as well as five new tracks. All songs on the album were written by McKenna alone, with the exception of \"Listen to Your Friends\", which was co-written with [[Rostam Batmanglij]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/gb/album/what-do-you-think-about-the-car/id1208110183|title=What Do You Think About the Car? (2017)|publisher=iTunes|access-date=12 April 2017}}</ref> McKenna played at various festivals in 2017, including [[Coachella Festival|Coachella]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.coachella.com/lineup |title=Lineup |publisher=Coachella |date= |accessdate=1 April 2017 |url-status= |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170320040746/https://www.coachella.com/lineup/ |archive-date=20 March 2017 |df= }}</ref> [[Lollapalooza]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/kot/ct-lollapalooza-2017-lineup-20170322-column.html|title=Lollapalooza 2017: Chance the Rapper, Lorde, Arcade Fire top 170-band lineup|date=22 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017|newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]]}}</ref> [[Glastonbury Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/newsbeat/article/39447179/declan-mckenna-and-alt-j-on-living-up-to-the-glastonbury-wow-factor|title=Declan McKenna and Alt J on living up to the Glastonbury 'wow-factor'|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=1 April 2017|publisher=[[BBC]]}}</ref> and [[Reading and Leeds Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.readingfestival.com/line-up/poster|title=Line Up Poster|date=30 March 2017|accessdate=7 April 2017|publisher=[[Reading and Leeds Festival]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413235607/http://www.readingfestival.com/line-up/poster|archive-date=13 April 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, McKenna won the [[BBC Music Awards|BBC Music Award]] for [[BBC Introducing]] Artist of the Year.<ref>{{cite news|title=BBC Music Awards 2017 announce Declan McKenna as BBC Music Introducing Artist Of The Year|work=BBC|date=6 December 2017|accessdate=2 January 2018|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/mediacentre/latestnews/2017/bbc-music-introducing-declan-mckenna}}</ref> He also appeared at the Pilton Party 2017 with [[Bastille (band)|Bastille]].<ref>http://www.glastonburyfestivals.co.uk/information/pilton-party-2017</ref> On 17 January 2018 McKenna released a music video for \"Make Me Your Queen\".\n\n===''Zeros'' (2019\u2013present)===\n\nOn 19 August 2019, McKenna released the song \"British Bombs\", which criticises UK foreign policy. He stated that it is specifically about \"the hypocrisy of the British arms trade and the weapons convention in London\". He wrote it as a result of wanting to write a song directly addressing war.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/declan-mc-kenna-opens-up-politically-charged-new-single-british-bombs-2539718 |title=Exclusive \u2013 Declan McKenna opens up about his politically charged new single 'British Bombs' |last=Aubrey |first=Elizabeth |date=19 August 2019 |website=[[NME]] |access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> McKenna later announced via [[Twitter]] on 18 December that his upcoming second studio album was mastered and ready for release. He also had an artwork shoot for the album on the same day.<ref>{{Cite tweet |number=1207381266812801024 |user=DeclanMcKenna |title=album is mastered and ready. artwork shoot today went hard. holy crapola. she\u2019s alive. happy holidays x |author=Declan McKenna |date=18 December 2019 |access-date=19 December 2019}}</ref> On 29 January 2020, McKenna revealed that his second album would be titled ''Zeros'' and be released on 15 May 2020. However, due to Covid-19 he, on the 24th of march 2020, postponed the album, and would, therefore, be released on 21 August 2020. He also released the song \"Beautiful Faces\" as the album's lead single.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://diymag.com/2020/01/30/declan-mckenna-new-album-zeros-watch-new-video-beautiful-people |title=Declan McKenna announces new album 'Zeroes' |date=30 January 2020 |website=[[DIY (magazine)|DIY]] |access-date=30 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Critical response==\nMcKenna writes his own songs, but is supported by a band on tour currently consisting of Isabel Torres (''guitarist''), Nathan Cox (''keys''), William Bishop (''bass'') and Gabrielle Marie King (''drummer'')<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHocldC9C8g&ab_channel=DeclanUpdated</ref>,  although he has previously played all of his own instruments.<ref name=brinsford /> In terms of the development of his musical style, he says he would most like to emulate [[David Bowie]]'s career.<ref name=savage />\n\n[[BBC News]] called \"Brazil\" an extraordinarily mature song for a 16-year-old songwriter.<ref name=bbc /> Matt Wilkinson at ''NME'' called it \"one of the best songs\" of 2015, and had high praise for McKenna's second single, \"Paracetamol\", as well.<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons of ThisNewBand.com called \"Brazil\" \"a catchy song no doubt\", and also noted that it was \"a sharp critique on sports, money and power.\"<ref name=lyons>{{cite web|url=http://thisnewband.com/837/meet-16-year-old-declan-mckenna-and-his-incredible-song-brazil/|last=Lyons|first=Jon|title=Meet 16-Year-Old Declan McKenna and His Incredible Song \"Brazil\"|website=ThisNewBand.com|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=8 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107100125/http://thisnewband.com/837/meet-16-year-old-declan-mckenna-and-his-incredible-song-brazil/|archive-date=7 January 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nSome music critics have tempered their praise of McKenna. Matt Wilkinson called McKenna's London gigs surprisingly good, if \"rough around the edges\".<ref name=wilkinson/> Jon Lyons has observed that as of November 2015, McKenna's songs seemed to indicate an artist still experimenting with bands and styles of music which have influenced him. He felt McKenna was still \"searching for his own sound right in front of the crowd. An artist is being born note by note.\"<ref name=lyons /> Andy Welch, music critic for the ''[[Bristol Post]]'', said McKenna was \"one to watch\", displaying \"lots of early, ragged promise\".<ref name=\"welch\" /> Grammy winning singer Adele commented in an interview \"He's so talented. I praise him for work so hard and doing so well at such a young age.\"\n\nAndre Paine of the ''[[Evening Standard]]'' was less impressed with McKenna's live show, commenting that although his performance \"had plenty of energy ... [he] didn't quite live up to his reputation as the voice of a generation\", going on to call McKenna's performance \"messy\".<ref name=Paine>{{cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/goingout/music/declan-mckenna-tour-review-not-quite-the-voice-of-a-generation-a3547376.html|last=Paine|first=Andre |title= Declan McKenna, tour review: Not quite the voice of a generation|website=Standard.co.uk|date=24 May 2017|accessdate=23 June 2017}}</ref> Liam Gallagher has also been critical of McKenna's music, commenting that it was simply \"not for me\".<ref>{{Citation|last=VICE News|title=Liam Gallagher's Weekly Music Corner Ep. 3 (HBO)|date=2017-10-11|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZqZa3-24Gro|accessdate=2018-04-10}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcKenna acknowledges that he is seen as a \"political\" or \"protest\" singer. He does not see himself as someone \"leading the conversation\" but rather as a person singing about things his peers are already talking about.<ref name=smithinterviewed /> For much of his initial work, McKenna said he tried to find inspiration for lyrics and topics in his private life. He felt his own life to be so uneventful, however, that he turned to political and social issues which he felt needed to be discussed.<ref name=savage /> For his second album, however, McKenna feels that he has had so much happen that he can draw on more personal experiences for his lyrics.<ref name=norris>{{cite news|last=Norris|first=John|title=With Politics, Eye Makeup and That Album Cover, Declan McKenna Goes Bold|work=Billboard|date=15 August 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7905012/declan-mckenna-politics-interview}}</ref>\n\nMcKenna says he feels good about being a role model.<ref name=smithinterviewed /> At first, he said he also struggled to understand both the criticism and praise he received, but has been able to be more mature and more analytical about both.<ref name=norris />\n\nAfter adopting a somewhat [[glam rock]] visual style for his live performances (which included extensive use of eye makeup and [[glitter]]),<ref name=savage /> McKenna addressed questions about his sexuality with ''[[Attitude (magazine)|Attitude]]'' magazine by declining to label himself. \"I'm young. I'm here to be experimented with\", he said, and told the interviewer that he is \"learning about a lot of things\". He was not being coy, he said, just honest about where he was in his life.<ref>{{cite news|title=Singer Declan McKenna On Ditching Labels: 'I'm Here to Be Experimented With'|work=Attitude|date=3 July 2017|accessdate=9 October 2018|url=https://attitude.co.uk/article/singer-declan-mckenna-on-ditching-labels-im-here-to-be-experimented-with/15173/}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of studio albums\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:20em;\"| Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:19em;\"| Details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"5\"| Peak chart positions\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[UK Albums Chart|UK]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/artist/49073/declan-mckenna/ |title=Declan McKenna : full Official Charts history |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Ultratop|BEL<br/>(FL)]]<br/><ref name=\"BEL FL\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.ultratop.be/nl/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Declan+McKenna |title=Discografie Declan McKenna |website=[[Ultratop]] |language=Dutch |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Irish Albums Chart|IRE]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/irish-albums-chart/20170728/ie7502/ |title=Official Irish Albums Chart Top 50 : 28 July 2017 \u2013 03 August 2017 |date=28 July 2017 |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Official Charts Company|SCO]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-albums-chart/20170728/40/ |title=Official Scottish Albums Chart Top 100 : 28 July 2017 \u2013 03 August 2017 |date=28 July 2017 |website=[[Official Charts Company]] |access-date=13 August 2017}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%;\"| [[Top Heatseekers|US<br/>Heat]]<br/><ref>{{Cite web |url=htt