{"title_page": "The Angel of Pennsylvania Avenue", "text_new": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name           = The Angel of Pennsylvania Avenue\n| image          = The_Angel_of_Pennsylvania_Avenue-1416008589.jpg\n| caption        =\n| genre          = Drama\n| director       = [[Robert Ellis Miller]]\n| writer         = Rider McDowell<br>Michael De Guzman\n| executive_producer = Craig Anderson\n| producer       = Tom Rowe<br>Lisa Towers<br>Rider McDowell (co-producer)\n| starring       = [[Diana Scarwid]]<br>[[Robert Urich]]<br>[[Tegan Moss]]\n| music          = Simon Kendall<br>Al Rodger\n| cinematography = [[David Geddes (cinematographer)|David Geddes]]\n| location       = [[Vancouver]]\n| editor         = Robert K. Lambert\n| company        = [[International Family Entertainment, Inc.]]<br>[[Hallmark Entertainment]]<br>Craig Anderson Productions<br>Pacific Motion Pictures<br>Signboard Hill Productions\n| distributor    =\n| network        = [[The Family Channel (American TV network, founded 1980)|The Family Channel]]\n| released       = {{Film date|1996|12|15|TV=y}}\n| runtime        = 92 mins.\n| country        = [[United States]]\n| language       = English\n| budget         =\n| gross          =\n| website        =\n| amg_id         =\n}}\n'''''The Angel of Pennsylvania Avenue''''' is an American 1996 television film directed by [[Robert Ellis Miller]], the last film Miller directed before his death on January 27, 2017. It was nominated for two [[Young Artist Awards]] in 1997.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0115543/awards</ref> The film was completed days before actor [[Robert Urich]] had surgery for cancer.<ref>{{cite book|title=TV Guide December 14-19, 1996. pg. 130}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nDuring the [[Great Depression]], an unemployed [[Detroit]] man is arrested for a crime he didn't commit, prompting his three children to travel 1,000 miles to the [[White House]] in search of help from President [[Herbert Hoover]] in order to have their father home for Christmas.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Diana Scarwid]] as Annie Feagan\n*[[Robert Urich]] as Angus Feagan\n*[[Tegan Moss]] as Bernice Feagan\n*[[Britt Irvin]] as Lily Feagan\n*[[Alexander Pollock]] as Jack Feagan\n* Camille Mitchell as Margaret\n*[[Thomas Peacocke]] as President [[Herbert Hoover]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0115543|title=The Angel of Pennsylvania Avenue}}\n\n{{Robert Ellis Miller}}\n{{ABC Family Original Movies}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Angel Of Pennsylvania Avenue}}\n[[Category:1996 television films]]\n[[Category:1990s Christmas films]]\n[[Category:1990s drama films]]\n[[Category:ABC Family original films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American Christmas films]]\n[[Category:American drama films]]\n[[Category:Films about Presidents of the United States]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Robert Ellis Miller]]\n[[Category:Great Depression films]]\n[[Category:Christmas television films]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Herbert Hoover]]\n\n{{Christmas-tv-film-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox television\n| show_name           = The Angel of Pennsylvania Avenue\n| image          = The_Angel_of_Pennsylvania_Avenue-1416008589.jpg\n| caption        =\n| genre          = Drama\n| director       = [[Robert Ellis Miller]]\n| writer         = Rider McDowell<br>Michael De Guzman\n| executive_producer = Craig Anderson\n| producer       = Tom Rowe<br>Lisa Towers<br>Rider McDowell (co-producer)\n| starring       = [[Diana Scarwid]]<br>[[Robert Urich]]<br>[[Tegan Moss]]\n| music          = Simon Kendall<br>Al Rodger\n| cinematography = [[David Geddes (cinematographer)|David Geddes]]\n| location       = [[Vancouver]]\n| editor         = Robert K. Lambert\n| company        = [[International Family Entertainment, Inc.]]<br>[[Hallmark Entertainment]]<br>Craig Anderson Productions<br>Pacific Motion Pictures<br>Signboard Hill Productions\n| distributor    =\n| network        = [[The Family Channel (United States)|The Family Channel]]\n| rel